That's &quot;snorkeling,&quot; not &quot;snorkling.&quot;  Of course, when I get water down the wrong tube, it could be &quot;snortingc&quot;  The river sure is cold this time of year.  Should wear a wet suit, I guess.<br><br>
I see a lot of committed people, but also a lot who try to make excuses for either themselves or others.  <br><br>
There are new developments on Jolly 365.  The latest issue of Canopy Chatter, the Pararescue Association Newsletter, had information on the ceremonies, which will be at 1100 hours, Nov. 19th.  There will also be a flyby of a Jolly Green.  I hope to post the information on the Jolly 365 site soon.  <br><br>
One other piece of information--my account of hand-held heat seeking missiles is not, repeat not, supported by eye-witness accounts of the downing.  My information was from the usual rumor-mill inside the USAF at the time.  A new book is due out in the Spring of 1998 titled &quot;The Rescue of Bat 21 by Darrel Whitcomb.  In it there is a detailed account of the loss of Jolly Green 67 (it's call sign, not it's tail number).  He described the Jolly Green 67 mission.<br><br>
&quot;As it came to a hover over Bat 21 Bravo, it was raked by heavy enemy fire.  The escorting Sandy A-1s tried to engage the enemy guns.  They could not pet them all.  They could see what the ground fire was doing to the helicopter.  Several shouted for the crew to fly out of the area.  The crew of Jolly Green 67 aborted the rescue attempt and tried to maneuver their stricken aircraft to safety.  The enemy fire continued and so damaged the crahy that it crashed in a huge fireball a few kilometers south of the survivors.  The fire was intense and lasted several days.  There were never any indications of survivors.&quot;<br><br>
I guess these guys would be called extremists today--who would be this dedicated to saving another's life.  A little crazy?  Well, I'd rather have them for friends than some of the other who would call a Marine an &quot;extremist.&quot;<br><br>
By the way, the person who planned and directed the rescue of Bat 21 Bravo was Lt. Col. Andy Anderson, A U.S. Marine.  The team that went in was a US Navy SEAL team, led by LT Tom Norris.  They rescued both Lt. Col. Hambleton and 1Lt Clark.  Lt. Tom Norris later received the Medal of Honor for the mission.
